{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_frannie_ver01/data/sn86072160/00514150345/1920092501/0657.xml":{"full_text":"INDICTMENTS PROBABLE IN WHITE SC* SCA\u201c\u2019TL\n\u00ael?v (Cciiiprr tkulif\nWEATHER FORECAST ts c. a\nFair tonight and Sunday; tome- g W\\ S3MS I\u201c SS\nwhat warmer m central portion H &R|d| j! ijP\ntonight. W -V W W K c *N. W. Arrive. Leave.\nNo. 606 Eastbound ._2.35 pan. Ztt pan.\n2 No. 603 Westbound__32o pan. 3:40 pan.\nVOLUME IV\nDouglas Light Plant Is\nFired Up After Receiver\nIs Appointed by Court\nNormal Conditions Restored After City\nGoes Without Light or Power for Two\nDays; Rate Increase Turned Down by\nState Commission May Be Granted Now\n(Special to The Tribune)\nDOUGLAS, Wyo., Sept. 25.-\u2014The Douglas Electric Light Com-'\npany fired np under its boilers again this morning after the city had!\nbeen without light and power since 6 o\u2019clock Thursday evening when\nthe company carried out its decision to discontinue servce of all kinds\nand cease operation.. Normal conditions will be restored in a few\nhours, it is believed, although it will take longer to recover from the!\ninconvenience caused during the past\ntwo days, particularly among those\nwho depended upon the electric com\npany for power.\nResumption of operations was made\npossible through an application for a\nreceivership granted by Judge Ralph\nKimball in district court. Friendly 1\nsuit was instituted as an emergency\nmeasure and John Yokum was ap\npointed receiver for the company on\nthe application of Burt Thompson, act\ning for the Morton estate, which is\nstill heavily Interested in pie\nJames A'. Ward, formerly of Casper, is\npresident of the company.\nSuspension of operations by the com\npany followed the refusal of the pub\nlic service commission of Wyoming to\ngrant an increase in rates wltfch' the\nlight company declared was neqessary\nto keep the company on an operating\nbasis. It is now probable that this in\ncrease will be granted, although action\nwill await the recommendations of the\nreceiver.\nH. M. Huntington of Cheyenne, a\nmember of the public service commis\nsion, was in Douglas Friday when the\nreceivership was granted.\nTwenty residents of Douglas gave\nbond to insure the receiver against loss\nin the operation of the plant. Company\nassets are plac'ed at >107.000, on which\na monthly income of >4.000 is realized,\nwhile expanses are said to amount to.\n>6,000 a month.\nProspects that the plant will be I\ntsiken over by the city to be operated\nas a municipal plant are held out. This 1\ncourse would require the calling of a\nspecial election to vote the necessary\nbonds.\nCHICAGO FLYER\nNAIL COACH IS\nROBBED TODAY\n(By United Press)\nCHICAGO, Sept. 2S\u00ab\u2014Masked ban\ndits robbed the mail car of the Illi\nnois Central flyer as the train was\napproaching Chicago early today and\nescaped with the contents of six reg\nistered mail pouches believed to con\ntain between 310,000 and 380.000.\nTwo robbers bound five mail clerks\nafter boarding the train in the sub\nurbs and rifled the sacks, escaping\nas the train slowed down.\n(By Associated Press)\nCHICAGO, Sept. 25.\u2014Two men\nwere arrested today as suspects In\nthe robbery last night of the north\nbound Illinois Central New Orleans\nlimited. Only registered mail of un\nknown value was taken. One man\nanswers the description of the band\nits.\nSTABILITY IS\nHARDING\u2019S AIM\n(By Associated Press.)\nMARION, Sept. 25.\u2014-An era of business stability and business-like gov\nernment were promised by Senator Warren G. Harding at a front porch speech\ntoday to a gathering of several thousand commercial travelers, who came\nfrom all parts of the country under the auspices of the Harding-Coolidge\nTraveling Men\u2019s League. Business methods of the Democratic administra\ntion, both in the conduct of Its own affairs and Its relations to private enter\nprise, were denounced by Harding as meddling and autocratic to a degree\nthreatening industrial chaos.\nI\nCASPER, WYO., SATURDAY, SEPT. 25, 1920\nt\nTWO MEXICAN STATES IN REVOLT\nREBELS IN CONTROL GOVERNMENT\n11\n(By Assoeiated.Press.)\nMEXICO CITY, Sept. .25.\u2014Governmental cuntroiof the of Aguas\nalientes has been seized by Gen. Martin Triana, according to pres. 4 dis\npatches, which said that Senor de Lara was chosen to head the state govern\nment by the chamber of deputies. Reports indicate that the city of Aguas\nCalient es is alarmed, but no disorders have taken place.\nThe coup d\u2019etat follows a similar Incident in the State of Michoacan,\nwhere Gen. Francisco Mujica recently assumed the powers of governor.\nSensational reports of disorders in Morelia, capital of Michoacan, have not\nbeen confirmed.\nBID ,'Llllt SLATED FDR WOMEN\n\nMHMPDOGRAM IS ISSUED\n1 1\n11 v\ni Local committees are rapidly finishing the work assigned them in\npreparation for the seventeenth annual convention of the Wyoming\nFederation of Women\u2019s Clubs, which is to be held here for three days\nnext week, beginning Wednesday morning.\nThe program in the federation colors, old gold and blue, has been\nprepared under the direction of Miss May Hamilton, assisted by Mrs.\n.W. V. Gage of Worland and Mrs. W. J.\nof this city.\nIt contains, in addition to the sched-,\nule of events for the convention, a list\n.of the officers and committees, and\nblank pages for the convenience of\ndelegates who may wish to take notes\ngluring the sessions, all atractlvely ar- i\nranged in notebook form.\nParticular attention has been paid to\nthe programs for the evening sessions.\nOn the first evening, formal ad\ndresses of welcome will be delivered,\nIMayor Pelton speaking for the city\nfind Mrs. B. B. Brooks for he club\nwomen. Mrs. W. V. Gage will make\nthe response, and this will be followed\nby .the president's address, delivered\nby Mrs. Lin I. Noble, federation presi\ndent. Dr. Grace 'Raymond Hebard will\nthen sneak on \u201cAmericanization.\u201d\nSpecial music will be provided for\nall sessions and will be a particular\nj feature of the Thursday evening ses-1\nsion, when Mrs. Anne F. Oberndorfer I\ni will speak on \u201cAmericanization\nThrough Music.\u201d\nCommitted reports and rtports of\nBjW Z m\nqIjB\n25\u00ae\ni UNION JACKS FLOAT FROM HOUSES IN BELFAST: Union Jacks flying from the windows of the homes in Lime\nStreet, Belfast, Ireland, during the recent rioting there. Unionists, roaming the streets in bands, pillaged and burned\nthe homes of Sinn Feiners. It is said that Inhabitants of the city. In order to save their homes, flew the Union Jack,\ndisplaying their spirit during the factionist fioting.\nstate officers will take up much of the\ntime during the morning and after\n..'noon sessions.\nJ The social features including a re\nl ception Wednesday evening and a ban-\nquet Friday evening, will be partlcular\ni pleasing.\nOCEAN OF BEER\nMINGLES WITH\ni RIVER WATERS\n1 CHICAGO, Sept. 15.\u2014Twenty-one\nthousand bottles of real beer were pour-\ned Into the Chicago river today by\ndeputy United States marshals.\n\u25a0JAPAN ASKED TO\nt SETTLE DISPUTE\nWITH CHINESE\n(By Associated Press.)\nTOK 10, Sept. 25^\u2014Speedy settle\nment of questions pending between\nJapan and China, including the early\nwithdrawal of Japanese troops from\nShantung and a solution of the Tsing\nTau question, was advised today by\nthe China-Japanese Business associa\ntion In a communication sent to Pre\nmier Hara. This association is head\ned by Viscount Eilchl Slilbusawa, a\nconservative leader.\nREXALLVOTE\nThe Kimball-Rexa.il straw vote for\npresident today stood:\nHarding\u2014Men, 1,154; women, 484; I\ntotal. 1,638. 1\nCox\u2014Men, 731; women, 264; total 995.\nNUMBER 297\nBusiness Outlook Good\nFor Remainder of Year,\nNational Chamber Says\nDisturbing Factors Passing Away With\nException of Automobile Industry, Is\nPromised Now; Export and Import\nTrade Falls Off Sharply During Month\n(By Associated Press.)\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 25.\u2014G00d business for the rest of the year\ndespite disturbing factors in the commercial, industrial and agricultur\nal outlook, is predicted in a report made public today by the commit\ntee on statistics and standards of the Chamber of Commerce of the\nUnited States. The report, which deals with conditions as observed\nthis month, describes buying as of a liberal volume, but on a sane and\nCOX SPEAKS AT\nLARAMIE TODAY\n(By Associated Press.)\nGREELEY, Colo., Sept. 25.\u2014A rear'\nplatform address here this morning\nconcluded the Colorado campaign of,\nGpv. James M. Cox and the remainder\nof the day will be spent in Wyoming,\nwith speeches late tl.is afternoon at\nLaramie and tonight at Cheyenne. The\nLeague of Nations, progressivism and\nagricultural topics were the principle\nthemes of Cox\u2019s addres here en route\nfrom Denver, where last night he cx-t\npanded on charges of conspiracy by\n[Chairman Will Hays and Republicans!\nto suppress newspaper publicity.\nCox declared that if elected he would\nrefer the Irish question to the league.\nCox answered questions asked by mem-|\nbera of the audience. He scored the\nRepublican candidates\u2019 \u201creactionary\nmethods\" and the \u201csenatorial olig-\nfcrehy.\" He also declared that he was\nconfident of victory In November.\nRUNAWAY GIHLS FOUND\nWITH MENIN CHEYENNE\nCHEYENNE. Wyo., Sept. 25.\u2014Maud\nMock, 14, and Alice Comley, 17, run\naways from Greybull, Wyo., were ar\nrested here Wednesday night in a\nroom at the Dyer hotel which they\nwere occupying with -M. G. Bradley and\nE. L. Mock, each apparently alxyut 30\nyears of age. The quartet eloped from\nGreybull a week ago and had been\nstopping at the Dyer house for throe\ndays. They occupied one room with\ntwin beds. When surprised by the po\nlice they insisted that they were broth\ners and sisters but the Mock child fi\nnally broke down and confessed the\nj truth of the situation. girls are\nheld for their parents. The men prob-1\nably will face trial for felony.\nI Evidence More Than Sufficient to b>\nFormal Charges, Grand Jury Foremari\nIndicates; Comiskey to Discharge Any\nPlayers Involved at Cost of Pennant\n(By Associated Press.)\nCHICAGO, Sept. 25.\u2014Indictments based on charges of conspiracy\nto defraud may be the result of the Cook County grand jury investiga\ntion of alleged crookedness on the part of players in last fall\u2019s world\nseries, were indicated today by Henry H. Brigham, foreman of the\njury. There seems to be more than sufficient evidence to support the\ncharges, Brigham declared.\ni sober busla of needs as contrasted to\nt the speculative purchasing of previous\nj months.\ni The committee says a cloud has ap\npeared on the automobile horizon\n1 which, it adds, seems to presage very\nj definitely lessened production in the I\nnear future and probably different and\nmore economical methods of dlstribu\ntlon.\nINTERNATIONAL TRADE\nSLUMPS IN AUGUST.\n(By Associated Press.)\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 25.\u201480th ex\nports and imports fell off sharply in\nAugust, figures issued today by the de\npartment of commerce show that ex\nports totalled >584,000,000, a decrease\nof >67,000,000 from July, and imports!\namounted to >519,000,000, a decrease of I\n515.000,000.\nWHEAT FUTURES\nTUMBLE AGAIN\nST. LOUIS. Sept. 26.\u2014Prices for\nwheat futures dropped an average of\n7V4 cents a bushel on the Merchants\u2019\nexchange here today, bringing the to\ntal decline of the week up to 30 cents.\n10,000 REDS CAPTURED\nBY GENERAL WRANGEL IN\nGREAT DRIVE IN SOUTH\n(By Associated Press.)\nSEBASTOPOL, Sept. 25.\u2014Gen. Baron Peter W ran gel,\nwho is opposing Russian Bolshevik forces on the southern\nfront, has taken .more than 10,000 prisoners in six days.\nCavalry forces are surrounding the Bolshevik! along a\n1 front of 100 miles, and are now reported to be outflanking\n'I\nI Red forces on the Dnieper River.\nI\n(By United Press.)\nI CHICAGO, Sept. 25.\u2014The grand jury\nInvestigation of the alleged world series\n\u25a0gambling seandnl bust year Is reported\nto have the names of several men con\nnected with the plot. Betting men of\nfervd >IOO,OOO to have the world series\nof 1919 thrown by the While Sox, it\nis reported.\nCharles Comiskey, owner of the Sox,\ndeclared today that he would discharge\nmembers of his team indicted by the\ngrand jury, even though it cost him\nthe pennant this year. Prominent baH\nplayehs and officials will be called be\nfore the grand jury on Tuesday.\nDEMOCRATS PUT\nUP MONEY FOR\nSOLDIER PAPER\nI\n(By United Press)\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 25.\u2014Mrs. R.\nM. Parks told the senate committee to\nday that W. D. Jamieson, finance di\nrector of the Democratic committee,\nadvanced her >4,000 to put in the\n\u201cStars and Stripes,\u201d a soldier publi\ncation. <Mrs. Parks, who was Jamie-\nIson's secretary, refused to divulge the\nnames of other Democratic contribut\nors.\n(By United Press)\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 25.\u2014Following\nleads recently received, the senate in-\nI vest igating committee next intends to\nI investigate the alleged lavish use of\nmoney and influence in several state\nprimary campaigns this year. Senator\nKenyon announced that the committee\nwould adjourn today and meet in St.\nLouis October 18 to complete the in-\nI vestigation started there some time\nago.\nI WASHINaTON. Sept. 26 \u2014fl. M. Ba\nj ructi of NeW yci\u00bb% *nd Secretary\nMeredith of the department of agricul\nture. were assessed as Democrats to\nfinance the publication of the soldier\npaper, \u201cStars and Stripes,\u201d Richard H.\nWaldo of New York\" stated today be\nfore the senate comfnittee invj&lgat-\nIng campaign expenditures. 'ssfaldo\nsaid Baruch furnished >7,000\ndith >2,500, which# they did pot\npect to get back.\nBODY OF^OLIVE\nTHOMAS ARRIVES\nAT N. Y. TODAY\n(By United Press)\nNEW YORK. Sept. 25.\u2014The body of\nOlive Thomas, motion picture star who\ndied from mercurial poisoning in Paris\narrived on the liner Mauretania today.\nThe body was accompanied by Jack\nPickford, her husband, and Owen\nMoore.\nM SWINEY SAID\nTO BE DEAD, NO\nNEWS IS ISSUED\n(By United Press)\nIXINDON, Sept. 25.\u2014A1l Inform v\ntion in regard to the condition <>f\nTerence MacSwiuey is being with\nheld today at Brixton prison. As a\nresult, rumors spread that Mac-\nSwiney was near death. This is the\n44th day of his hunger strike.\nanother bank\nCONCERN HITS\nROCK, BOSTON\n(By Associated Press.)\nBOSTON, Sept.\u20142s.\u2014The Cosmopoll-i\ntan Trust Company of this city, with'\nsavings and a banking department and\nagencies abroad, was closed today by\nBank Commissioner Joseph C. Allen.\n(By United Press.)\nLONDON, Sept. 25.\u2014Gen. Budeny, famous Bolshe\nvik! leader, is reported to have been severely wounded dur\ning a Ukraine battle.\nResumption of Polish-Russian hostilities on a big\nscale is believed imminent on the receipt of information\nthat the Reds are concentrating a large force of Siberian\ntroops near Grodno. An offensive on Brest-IJtovsk la be\nlieved imminent.\nOroei ror\nRail Sale\nIs Issued\n1 __\nPetition of stock\nholders Refused by\nCourt; D. R-\nto Go on Block\n(By Associated Press)\nDENVER, Sept. 25.\u2014An order\nthe sale of the Denver Rio Grande\nrailroad was signed in federal court\ntoday by Judge Walter 11. Sandborn.\nThe order was the result of action\nbrought by the Equitable Trust com\npany of New York. The petition of a\nstockholders\u2019 committee for postpone*\nment was denied. The order mus*.\nsigned by Judge Robert E. Lewis also\nbefore it becomes effective. Judge\nLewis is out of the city.\nWilliam A. Jackson, special master\nwas ordered to advertise the sale <\u00bbf\nthe road four weeks before the sale\nto satisfy a judgment of $36,-\n197,411.43.\n$1,682,38811111\nBE TOTAL STATE\nTAX COLLECTION\nRepresents Proceeds from Levy\nof 3.98 Mills; Less Needed for\nState Hospitals Through\nTaxation, Claim\n(Special to The Tribune I\nCHEYENNE, Wyo.. Sept. 25. The\nstate of Wyoming will raise for gov\nernmental purposes, through direct\ntaxation, this year $1,682,388.99. This\nwill be /the proceeds from the state\nlevy of 3.98 mills on tho 1920 assessed\nvaluatloh of $422,987,183. The levy la\nwithin two one-hundredths of the legal\nlimit of 4 mills.\nOs the state levy, 2.676 mills is for\nthe general fund, ,3C7 of a mill for\nhighway bonds Interest, .04 of a mill\nfor territorial tufods interest, .125 of a\n\u2022mill for a new state bridge at Ther\nmopolis, .5 of a ntill for the state unl\nvarsity, .061 of a the state capl\ntol building maintenance\u2019 fund and .013\nof a mill for each of jhe three state\nhospitals. In nine counties there will\nbe collected by the state! the proceed*\nof a .021 of a mill tax for higtr\nschools.\nTho .012 of a mill tax for each of the\nthree state hospitals will'raise approxi\nmately $5,000 for each. In precedin'?\nyears it has l*een necessary to raise\nabout $15,000 for each hospital through,\ntaxation, but the land income fund and\nomnibus income fund of the hospitals,\ntogether with their revenues from pa\ntients, have become sufficient to re\u00ab\nduce the former levy about two-tldruM.\nKOREANS WRECK\nTOWN, STUDENTS\nLEADING RIOTS\n(By Associated Press.j\nTOK 10, Sept. 25.\u2014Advices from*\nSeoul report that 600 Korean stu\ndents destroyed seven buildings, in-\u2019,\neluding the bank and police station\nin Genzan. Several Koreans were\nkilled.\nTHREEKiLLED\nBY EXPLOSION\nIN STEEL MILL\n(By United Press)\nJACKSON. Sept. 25.\u2014An explosion\nat the steel mills here today killed\nthree men and injured six. One of the\nfurnaces gave way and hot metal pour\ned out on the workmen.","height":"18888","width":"15100"}}
